                Quebec, Canada

        Posts
                2,789

     Yeah, I often think of things like that; Take by example a cube
     mapped with a red, uniform texture. Why use a red texture that takes
     memory and bandwidth when you can say to the hardware; You see that
     surface? Fill it with a color using an RGB value of 253,0,6. Then,
     apply those lighting patterns, etc...
     It would be less consuming on the hardware ressources, and simply
     changing the color parameters, hue, saturation, like you said would
     give the same results as using another texture to show the changes.
     Plus, it can be done in realtime; Imagine viewing the landscape of a
     big city going rapidly from day to night, using the same textures on
     the buildings and simply adjust the lighting values and make light
     coming out of the windows - not with a light texture - but an
     algorithm able to change the different degrees of light. It would
     make the video chipset to think more and map less. THAT would use
     that Hardware T&L.
     I clearly see your point of view with that, that Nature scene in
     3DMark 2001 looks pretty darn good, but runs at around 25 FPS
     average with a GF3. Nobody would want those kinds of averages in
     games. Sure it would be nice to render big huge trees with foliage,
     but entering in a forest of these in a game would make the FPS drop
     to a crawl, even on a GF3... that's a shame...Good showcase, but
     utterly useless in gaming for that generation of cards. Let's hope
     people just don't think that given they have a GF3, they will have a
     completely optimized landscape in games optimized for it...well they
     may have it, but running at 5 FPS. Just my 2 cents.
     ------------------
